**Special Relativity (1905)**

Albert Einstein, a young patent clerk in Bern, Switzerland, was working at the Swiss Patent Office when he had an epiphany that changed the course of physics. In 1905, he published four groundbreaking papers that introduced the special theory of relativity, which challenged the long-held notion of absolute time and space.

In his paper ""On the Electrodynamics of Moving Bodies,"" Einstein introduced the concept of time dilation, length contraction, and the famous equation E=mc². He showed that time and space are relative, and that the laws of physics are the same for all observers in uniform motion relative to one another.

**General Relativity (1915)**

Two years later, in 1915, Einstein expanded his theory to include gravity, introducing the concept of gravity as a curvature of spacetime caused by massive objects. In his paper ""On the Electrodynamics of Moving Bodies,"" he also introduced the famous equation G = 8πG/c², which describes the gravitational force between two objects.

Einstein's theory of general relativity revolutionized our understanding of gravity, space, and time. It predicted phenomena such as gravitational waves, black holes, and the bending of light around massive objects.

**Legacy**

Einstein's theory of relativity has had a profound impact on our understanding of the universe, from the behavior of subatomic particles to the expansion of the cosmos itself. It has been extensively tested and confirmed by numerous experiments and observations, including those conducted by scientists such as Robert Penrose, Kip Thorne, and Brian Greene.

Today, Einstein's theory of relativity is considered one of the most influential scientific theories of the 20th century, and it continues to shape our understanding of the universe and its many mysteries.

