meta-llama/llama-3.1-8b-instruct,1.5,101,Q10,noisy,what is the boiling point of water?,"The boiling point of water is typically around 212°F (100°C) at standard atmospheric pressure. However, please note that atmospheric pressure can affect the boiling point, and this temperature assumes a pressure of:

* 1 atm, sea level, etc.

Water's boiling point at elevated pressures can vary from 211°F to 221°(104°C to 105°C), and changes when lowered to 203.4° (95.2 Celsius).

This can all change at varying altitudes, due to changes in ambient temperatures, the vessel itself (depending on shape, surface area exposure, and other variables).

